{{merge from|Descriptive Video Service|discuss=Talk:Audio description#Proposed merge with Descriptive Video Service|date=July 2018}} {{multiple issues| {{Refimprove|date=December 2014}} {{External links|date=December 2014}} }}
'''Audio description''', also referred to as a '''video description''', '''described video''', or more precisely called a '''visual description''', is an additional [[narration]] track intended primarily for [[blindness|blind]] and [[visually impaired]] consumers of visual media (including [[television]] and [[film]], [[dance]], [[opera]], and [[visual art]]). It consists of a narrator talking through the presentation, describing what is happening on the screen or stage during the natural pauses in the audio, and sometimes during dialogue if deemed necessary.<ref name="definition">{{cite web|url=http://www.dcmp.org/descriptionkey/|title=Description Key for Educational Media|publisher=The Described and Captioned Media Program|date=November 4, 2008|accessdate=September 7, 2009}}</ref>
For the performing arts ([[theater]], [[dance]], [[opera]]), and media ([[television]], [[film|movies]] and [[DVD]]), description is a form of audio-visual translation, using the natural pauses in dialogue or between critical sound elements to insert narrative that translates the visual image into a sense form that is accessible to millions of individuals who otherwise lack full access to television and film. Occasionally when there is dialogue that is in another language from the main one of the film and subtitled on screen, the subtitles are read in character by the describer.{{citation needed lead|date=December 2014}}
In [[museums]] or visual art exhibitions, audio described tours (or universally designed tours that include description or the augmentation of existing recorded programs on audio- or videotape), are used to provide access to visitors who are blind or have low vision. Docents or tour guides can be trained to employ audio description in their presentations. Audio description of sporting events is now becoming more common, in particular at soccer stadiums.{{citation needed lead|date=December 2014}}
Researchers are working to show how description, through its use of varied word choice, synonyms, metaphor and simile, not only benefits children who are blind and others who have learning disabilities but can also boost literacy for all children.{{citation needed lead|date=December 2014}}
==History== In early 2009, the [[American Council of the Blind]] (ACB) established the Audio Description Project (ADP) to boost levels of description activity and disseminate information on that work throughout the United States and worldwide.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}
With respect to description and media, broadcast systems in Canada and the United States are transmitted digitally and access to description on the former SAP [[second audio program|secondary audio program]] channel is no longer available. Ideally, it is now possible to access multiple streams of audio, e.g., Spanish translation, audio description, audio description in Spanish, etc. In the United States, affiliates in the top 25 markets and the top five-rated cable network are required to provide 50 hours of video-described programming per quarter under the 21st Century Communications and Video Accessibility Act of 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Networks Set to Launch Video Descriptions|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/60097/networks-set-to-launch-video-descriptions|work=TVNewsCheck.com|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> [[Descriptive Video Service]] (DVS) is a popular producer of audio description for shows on television.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Media Access Group at WGBH|title=Who We Are|url=http://main.wgbh.org/wgbh/pages/mag/about/|website=WGBH|publisher=WGBH Educational Foundation|accessdate=12 June 2016}}</ref>
Similarly, the limited number of DVDs available with description in North America (less than 100—as compared to over 500 in the [[United Kingdom]] and over 700 in Australia<ref name=MediaAccessOz>{{cite web |url = http://www.mediaaccess.org.au/dvds/dvd_database |title = Audio described DVD Database |publisher = Media Access |location = Australia |accessdate = 10 December 2012 }}</ref>) is further complicated by the lack of an audio menu on no more than a handful of those DVDs.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}
In August 2009, [[BBC iPlayer]] became the first [[video on demand]] service to offer Audio Description.<ref name="iplayer09">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/bbcinternet/2009/08/bbc_iplayer_audio_description.html|title=BBC iPlayer audio description is now available|work=BBC Internet Blog|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=August 27, 2009|accessdate=September 7, 2009}}</ref>
In December 2015, [[The Wiz Live!]] was the first live TV program to contain audio description in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=American Foundation for the Blind Celebrates 20th Anniversary of the Helen Keller Achievement Awards and Announces 2016 Honorees|url=http://www.afb.org/info/about-us/press-room/press-release-archive/afb-announces-2016-helen-keller-achievement-awards-honorees-/1245|publisher=American Foundation for the Blind|accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref>
On June 17, 2016, [[Pornhub]] announced that it would launch a collection of [[pornographic video]]s with audio descriptions. The initiative is sponsored by the website's philanthropic arm Pornhub Cares.<ref name="vice-pornhubdvs">{{cite web|title=Pornhub Is Making Audio Porn for the Visually Impaired|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/read/pornhub-described-video-visually-impaired-vgtrn|website=Vice|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>
==Operation== Broadcast audio description in the U.K. is delivered digital terrestrially on a separate track containing the narration only, making it possible to adjust the AD volume separately from that of the main audio track from the television programme before the receiver mixing is performed. However, on digital receivers that lack any kind of audio pre-mixing ability such as is the case with a number of digital [[satellite television]] or [[cable television]] or [[Advanced Television Systems Committee standards|ATSC]] receivers, the AD track is provided with the narration already mixed in and has to be manually selected as either a [[Second audio program|SAP]] for ATSC or another language for DVB.
In movie theaters, audio description can be heard using DVS Theatrical and similar systems (including [[DTS-CSS]] and [[Dolby Screentalk]]). Users listen to the description on a [[wireless headset]].{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}
[[File:Audio describer in live theater.jpg|thumb|left|An audio describer working in a live theater. A small mixer and transmitter are visible, and the lit stage can be seen in the distance.]] In live theaters, patrons also receive the description via a wireless device, a discreet monaural receiver. However, the description is provided live by describers located in a booth acoustically insulated from the audience, but from where they have a good view of the performance. They make their description which is fed to a small radio transmitter.<ref name=VisionAustralia>{{cite web |url = http://www.visionaustralia.org/living-with-low-vision/learning-to-live-independently/sport-recreation-and-the-arts/enjoying-theatre-museums-galleries-and-cinema |title = Enjoying theatre, museums, galleries and cinema |publisher = [[Vision Australia]] |location = Australia |accessdate = 10 December 2012 }}</ref> It is possible to provide the facility to a theater entirely with portable equipment, delivered to the theater in two equipment cases of suitcase size.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}
The description of the performance can be augmented with tactile tours of the stage or costumes or both.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}
==Audio description logo==
Audio description logo can be used by equipment manufacturers i.e., television and set top box manufacturers, broadcasters, cinemas, theatres, DVD and Blu-ray disc production companies to convey that their services or products offer audio description. The logo makes it easier for people with sight loss to identify products which would be available with an additional audio description track.
This is a standard logo that has been in the UK for many years but it is now being adopted by service providers across countries to indicate that a product or service has audio description.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}} Other countries can have different logos, such as for example Sweden where different TV channels and organizations together created [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Synsymbol.jpg a Swedish standard].
The logo is available to download in various formats and sizes, as well as horizontal or vertical versions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acb.org/adp/ad.html#symbols|title=What is Audio Description?|first=Fred|last=Brack|website=www.acb.org}}</ref>
